The <b>build phase</b> involves the idea’s team building and subsequently, its prototype and business plan engineering. Here, the owner of the idea pitches the idea to the community and details the types of team members he would like as partners along with skills he hopes they can provide. Then, this team works together to help develop the idea into a minimum viable product (the core features of the product allowing it to be deployed, and no more). Users can write the idea’s description (its business model and specification for the prototype construction), write part of the business plan, design the frontend, or code/build the prototype. The team's contributions are rewarded with equity in the idea and an increase in their reputation points. Each user on Labthi.ng also has, on his profile, skill bars in each of the 4 key start-up development areas: idea planning, business plan writing, prototyping and designing/branding. Upon completing a part and gaining equity, your proficiency in each of these areas increases. You can then quote these skill bars as representations of your entrepreneurial skill building on your CV!
<br><br>
If you do not have prior experience writing business plans or building prototypes, it does not matter; for each part, we explain what its for, what is required, and how to structure it. We thus help you develop your skills in each of these 4 areas, and give you experience directly applying them to building and brainstorming start-ups of all kinds. <br>
<hr>

<div>
<a class='anchor' id='teambuild'></a>
  <h3><strong>Team Building</strong></h3><br>
  Here we explain the first part of the build phase: putting together the team behind the start-up. As soon as the idea is promoted into phase 2, the owner of the idea is notified to write a brief (pitch) for the idea, which is explained in detail below. This will be the community's base understanding of the idea: the product, its business model and its future goals. The creator is then told to write a <b>proposal</b> for the community, inviting candidates to apply to be team members of hte idea. 
  <hr>
  <h4><strong>Writing a Proposal</strong></h4><br>
  The proposal should include information about the current team member(s); their work ethics and personality characteristics, along with a brief description of their skillsets. Furthermore, it should include a description about what needs to be built in phase 2: what the goals for the idea by the end of phase 2 are and in how long they hope to complete them, what the current team member(s) are interested in building, and what they hope future team members will be interested in building. Then, there should be a description of the type of work ethic and skillsets the team hopes the future partners will have. Remember to be professional but friendly; you want the community to want to work with you. Also, try to be detailed in your explanations of the idea, its goals, and the skills needed for its phase 2 development, so that the community knows exactly what they are applying for and how to apply.
  <hr>
  <h4><strong>Applying to be a Team Member</strong></h4><br>
  Once this proposal is written, if a user clicks on the <b>build</b> tab in the navbar, and then the <b>needs team members</b> tab in the secondary navbar, he will see the idea listed as one with an open proposal; e.g., one looking for team members. Once he clicks on the <b>team build</b> section of the idea, he can choose to <b>apply to be a team member</b> under the proposal. When applying, you must explain how your skills and personality match those of the current team members. Explain your interest in the idea; why you like it, why your experience or knowledge can be valuable to the team, and why they should choose you to be a partner. Remember, it helps to have contributed in the brainstorming phase of the idea, since the owner and other users will already be familiar with your thinking and interest in the idea. <br><br>
  Attached to your application will be a detailed list of your contributions in the <b>create</b> phase; the number of questions, answers and solutions you have contributed, along with your local reputation. Furthermore, your skill bars from your profile will be attached to show the current team your experience and activity on the site. Do not worry if you do not have skills above 50%: this will never negatively affect your chances of being chosen. Everyone has to start somewhere.
  <hr>
  <h4><strong>Selecting a Team Member - Accepting an Application</strong></h4><br>
  If you think a candidate is a suitable partner for the idea and can contribute well, you can <b>accept</b> his application. All of the team members will vote on whether or not the candidate should be accepted. If, after all team members have read the application, more than 50% of the team has accepted it, the candidate is added to the team. <hr>
  <h4><strong>Next Steps</strong></h4><br>
  Once enough team members have been accepted and the team agrees that together they cover all of the necessary skills needed to complete phase 2, they can start building the idea. Here, they can move onto the <b>build</b> tab and begin starting parts and building content. When a team member finishes a part, other team members can leave him tasks and extra bits of content to improve the quality of his work. Once the team members all vote to accept it, the part is completed, the user is awarded proficiency in the appropriate skill area along with equity in the idea. He can then move onto starting and completing a new part.
  <br><br>Team members will also have access to the <b>discussion</b> tab, where they can generally discuss anything, regardless of whether it relates to the idea, its building or the team itself. Furthermore, each part has a <b>discussion</b> tab for discussing anything relating to that specific part.<br><br>We will proceed to explain the parts, their designated equity amounts, and what each part is.<hr>
