  The plan component is the idea description: the backbone of the <b>build phase</b>. All users building other parts have viewing access to this component, because it is the plan for the minimum viable product and business model of the idea. When the idea transitions into the <b>build phase</b>, this is the first part that must be built.
  <br><br>
  The business plan component details the business model of the product; business-related goals, why they are attainable and the plan for reaching these goals. Here, it will also detail the process by which the team who purchases the idea in the buy phase should further develop the product, the business and the marketing plan by which they should go about building the brand image and can successfully target the customer segment. Excluding the executive summary, every part of the business plan is independent and can be written without referencing each other. The executive summary, however, will be locked until the other parts are completed, as it consists of an in depth summary of each of the other business plan parts.
  <br><br>
  The design component regards the brand image of the product and the front end of the prototype. Users here will design the logo, the wireframes for the product (the page layouts for each page necessary to present the core functionality of the product), and the mock-ups for these wireframes (wireframes including styling and design elements that help define the brand image). The logo and wireframes can be completed independently without referencing each other; however, the user producing the mock-up has viewing privileges to both other parts in the design component as it is comprised of wireframes styled with the brand image.
  <br><br>
  Finally, the prototype component regards building the backend of the minimum viable product. This first part consists of planning the prototype; the flowchart and schema. The flowchart is a diagrammatic representation of the workflow and process by which a customer uses the product, and the schema consists of a simple plan of the database structure of the product’s backend. The second part, the prototype, is the product itself; the core features necessary to deploy the MVP, whose backend follows the schema and frontend follows the flowchart and resembles the mock-ups. It is worth the most amount of equity because it is the most time intensive part in the <b>build phase</b>, and the most valuable content being created.
